From: chris@thoday.demon.co.uk (EurIng Chris Thoday)
Subject: Re: Linux Consortium
Reply-To: chris@thoday.demon.co.uk
Date: Wed, 1 Dec 1993 21:46:08 +0000


Firstly the name: according to my dictionary a "consortium" is a
combination of countries, companies, or other groups acting together. I
don't think that the proposed Linux Consortium fits this definition.
Perhaps "Linux Distributions Review Group" would be better.

Is there a need for such a group? Just look at the complaints and cries
for help in the newsgroups. CD-ROM distributions are being sent out
with boot disks that just do not work. Unless you have access to the
Internet no amount of experience will help. In my case it takes nearly
two hours of a long-distance phone call to ftp a floppy disk worth of
code. Linux will get a bad name if distributors are allowed to
advertise what they cannot deliver. Until you have a working system
it not possible to get a documentation on the floppy disks or CD.

I would like to suggest that the review group should:

   a) Collect reports from anybody who wishes to report a problem.
   b) Attempt to verify the problem reports where possible.
   c) Maintain a database of solutions.
   d) Issue guidance to distributors.

In short, the aim would be to help people with problems and to help
distributors improve their products.

--
EurIng Chris Thoday,              chris@thoday.demon.co.uk, Software Engineer
8 Victoria Street, RUGBY,         a Director of the European X User Group Ltd
Warwickshire, CV21 2HN, UK        info@exug.demon.co.uk

