From: hwstock@snll-arpagw.llnl.gov (stockman harlan w)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux
Subject: Re: Linux on Pentium machine
Date: 1 Dec 93 16:16:02 GMT

In article <93329.100856YLCBC@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU> YLCBC@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU writes:
>Since I posted a short message to the net a few days ago, many people
>ask for more details. The Pentium machine is the Gateway2000 P5-60.
[...]
>a couple of numbers for you for reference:
>  BogoMip 23.9    (less than a 486DX50 at home, 24.9)

I don't know what BogoMip is, but every benchmark I have run on the
P5-60 substantially beats or at least matches the fastest 486/66v I can
find. These have been mainly scientific and academic-type benchmarks
like nsieve, FLOPS, linpack, heapsort, dhrystone, etc. My latest
c-linpack runs give 9.5 MFLOPS (double precision) for the P5-60, and 1.5
MFLOPS for a 486/33. I no longer have a 486/66 on hand, but past
experience would put it at about 2.8 MFLOPS.


