From: bcr@bohr.physics.purdue.edu (Bill C. Riemers)
Crossposted-To: comp.unix.misc,comp.unix.shell
Subject: Re: A script: to identify multiple executables on PATH
Date: 2 Dec 93 00:16:42 GMT

Ajay Shah <ajayshah@cmie.ernet.in> wrote:
>In some Linux distributions there have been duplicate binaries.
>This script will find them all.

If you really want to find duplicate files I find the following
script is very efficent:

/local/bin/same
---> Cut here <---
#!/bin/tcsh -f 
alias errors \
 'mknod /tmp/$$.\!:0 p;(cat /tmp/$$.\!:0 &);(\!:2-$ >/tmp/$$.\!:0 )>&\!:1;\rm -f
 /tmp/$$.\!:0'

set awk1=("{`cat`}") <<\+
  N=$1; 
  if(N==O && R != "T"){ 
    R="T";print L 
  }; 
  L="if (-f " $2 " & ! -l " $2 " ) eval 'echo `wc<" $2 "` `sum " $2 "`'";
  if(N==O){
    print L
  }else{
    O=N;R="F"
  } 
\+

set awk2=("{`cat`}") <<\+
  N=$1 " " $2 " " $3 " " $4 " " $5; 
  if(N==O){ 
    k=j; 
    for(i=1;i<=j;i++){ 
      if(system("cmp -s " $6 " " V[i])==0){ 
        print V[i] " " $6;break 
      }else{ 
        if(i==j){V[++k]=$6} 
      } 
    }; 
    j=k 
  }else{ 
    j=1;O=N;V[j]=$6 
  } 
\+

Main:
  if ( $#argv == 0 ) goto Usage
  foreach i ( $argv )
    if ! -d $i goto Usage
  end
  errors /dev/null (echo;du -a -b $1| \
    expand| \
    fgrep -v ' /proc/'| \
    sort -n| \
    awk "$awk1:q"|  \
    tcsh -f| \
    sort -u| \
    awk "$awk2:q" )
exit


Usage: 
  echo 'Find all files that are the same within a directory tree.'
  echo 'Usage: '"$0:t"' <tree names>'
exit

---> Cut Here <---

Occassionally I like to do something like:

same / > /tmp/$$
awk '{print "ln -f " $1 " " $2}' < /tmp/$$ |tcsh -v

Obcourse this will cause real problems if you ment to have multiple copies
of the same file.  So you might want to edit /tmp/$$ before running awk.

Hmmm..., it looks like tcsh 6.04 is reporting Segmentation faults if I do this
all in a pipe with 0.99pl14.   It looks like I'll have to search for the
binary that is broken with the new kernel...

                                 Bill
 

