From: longyear@netcom.com (Alfred Longyear)
Subject: Re: Linux CD-ROM Giveaway
Date: Thu, 2 Dec 1993 08:53:08 GMT

john.will@satalink.com (John Will) writes:

>Even though this is "a new distribution company", they're still associated
>with Jana in some way, the folks that took money months in advance for
>out of date CD-ROMs.

ANY CDROM WHICH YOU BUY FOR LINUX WILL BE OUT OF DATE.

This is a simple fact of life. If you buy a CDROM and expect to get the
"current" code then you are deluding yourself. The reason is that it takes
some finite amount of time to master the CDROM. During that time, the code
for Linux changes.

If you really want current code, then you must obtain it from the ftp
archive sites.

About the only thing that is current for CDROMs -- all of them -- is
SLS. Perhaps that says something about the release status of SLS ??

